# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1938-chicago-cubs-season
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1938-chicago-cubs-season/1871-chicago-white-stockings-season] The **1871 Chicago White Stockings season** was the second season of the Chicago White Stockings franchise, the first in the National Association of Professional Base Ball Players and the first at Union Base-Ball Grounds.
[src:1938-chicago-cubs-season/1871-chicago-white-stockings-season] With the debut of the first professional baseball league, the National Association, the Chicago franchise joined up as the "White Stockings." The team went 19–9 and finished second in the league standings.
[src:1938-chicago-cubs-season/1871-chicago-white-stockings-season] Pitcher George Zettlein started all 28 of Chicago's games and led the NA with a 2.73 earned run average.
[src:1938-chicago-cubs-season/1871-chicago-white-stockings-season] Near the end of the season, the team lost its stadiums and equipment when the Great Chicago Fire hit the city.
[src:1938-chicago-cubs-season/1871-chicago-white-stockings-season] The team was able to finish out the season on the road, but had to drop out of the league while the city attempted to recover.
[src:1938-chicago-cubs-season/1871-chicago-white-stockings-season] The team would not resurface until 1874.
[src:1938-chicago-cubs-season/1874-chicago-white-stockings-season] The **1874 Chicago White Stockings season** was the third season of the Chicago White Stockings franchise, the second in the National Association of Professional Base Ball Players and the first at 23rd Street Grounds.
[src:1938-chicago-cubs-season/1874-chicago-white-stockings-season] The White Stockings returned to the league in 1874 after taking two years to recover from the chaos of the Great Chicago Fire.
[src:1938-chicago-cubs-season/1874-chicago-white-stockings-season] They opened their season on Wednesday May 13 hosting the Philadelphia Athletics and shut them out 4 to 0.
[src:1938-chicago-cubs-season/1874-chicago-white-stockings-season] They finished fifth in the National Association with a record of 28–31.
[src:1938-chicago-cubs-season/1874-major-league-baseball-season] The following are the baseball events of the year 1874 throughout the world.
[src:1938-chicago-cubs-season/1875-chicago-white-stockings-season] The **1875 Chicago White Stockings season** was the fourth season of the Chicago White Stockings franchise, the third and final in the National Association of Professional Base Ball Players and the second at 23rd Street Grounds.
[src:1938-chicago-cubs-season/1875-chicago-white-stockings-season] The White Stockings finished sixth in the National Association with a record of 30–37–2.
[src:1938-chicago-cubs-season/1876-chicago-white-stockings-season] The **1876 Chicago White Stockings season** was the fifth season of the Chicago White Stockings franchise, the first in the National League and the third at 23rd Street Grounds.
[src:1938-chicago-cubs-season/1876-chicago-white-stockings-season] The White Stockings, as one of the founding members of the new National League, won the NL's initial championship during this season with a record of 52–14.
[src:1938-chicago-cubs-season/1877-boston-red-caps-season] The **1877 Boston Red Caps season** was the seventh season of the franchise.
[src:1938-chicago-cubs-season/1877-boston-red-caps-season] Arthur Soden became the new owner of the franchise, who won their first National League pennant.
[src:1938-chicago-cubs-season/1877-chicago-white-stockings-season] The **1877 Chicago White Stockings season** was the 6th season of the Chicago White Stockings franchise, the 2nd in the National League and the fourth at 23rd Street Grounds.
[src:1938-chicago-cubs-season/1877-chicago-white-stockings-season] The White Stockings finished fifth in the National League with a record of 26–33.
[src:1938-chicago-cubs-season/1938-chicago-cubs-season] The **1938 Chicago Cubs season** was the 67th season of the Chicago Cubs franchise, the 63rd in the National League and the 23rd at Wrigley Field.
[src:1938-chicago-cubs-season/1938-chicago-cubs-season] The Cubs finished first in the National League with a record of 89–63.
[src:1938-chicago-cubs-season/1938-chicago-cubs-season] The team was swept four games to none by the New York Yankees in the World Series.
[src:1938-chicago-cubs-season/1938-chicago-cubs-season] The team is known for the season of pitcher Dizzy Dean.
[src:1938-chicago-cubs-season/1938-chicago-cubs-season] While pitching for the NL in the 1937 All-Star Game, Dean suffered a big toe fracture.
[src:1938-chicago-cubs-season/1938-chicago-cubs-season] Coming back too soon from the injury, Dean changed his pitching motion to avoid landing too hard on his sore toe enough to affect his mechanics.
[src:1938-chicago-cubs-season/1938-chicago-cubs-season] As a result, he hurt his arm, losing his great fastball.
[src:1938-chicago-cubs-season/1938-chicago-cubs-season] Cubs scout Clarence "Pants" Rowland was tasked with the unenviable job of obeying owner Philip K.
[src:1938-chicago-cubs-season/1938-chicago-cubs-season] Wrigley's direct order to buy a washed-up Dean's contract at any cost.
[src:1938-chicago-cubs-season/1938-chicago-cubs-season] Rowland signed the ragged righty for $185,000, one of the most expensive loss-leader contracts in baseball history.
[src:1938-chicago-cubs-season/1938-chicago-cubs-season] Dean still helped the Cubs win the 1938 pennant.
[src:1938-chicago-cubs-season/1938-chicago-cubs-season] On July 20, Wrigley named 37-year-old Gabby Hartnett as the team's player-manager, replacing Charlie Grimm.
[src:1938-chicago-cubs-season/1938-chicago-cubs-season] When Hartnett took over, the Cubs were in third place, six games behind the first place Pittsburgh Pirates who were led by Pie Traynor.
[src:1938-chicago-cubs-season/1938-chicago-cubs-season] By September 27, with one week left in the season, the Cubs had battled back to within a game and a half game of the Pirates in the National League standings as the two teams met for a crucial three-game series.
[src:1938-chicago-cubs-season/1938-chicago-cubs-season] Dean pitched the opening game of the series and with his ailing arm, relied more on his experience and grit to defeat the Pirates by a score of 2 to 1.
[src:1938-chicago-cubs-season/1938-chicago-cubs-season] Dean would later call it the greatest outing of his career.
[src:1938-chicago-cubs-season/1938-chicago-cubs-season] The Cubs cut the Pirates' lead to a half game and set the stage for one of baseball's most memorable moments.
[src:1938-chicago-cubs-season/1938-chicago-cubs-season] On September 28, the two teams met for the second game of the series, where Hartnett experienced the highlight of his career.
[src:1938-chicago-cubs-season/1938-chicago-cubs-season] With darkness descending on the lightless Wrigley Field and the score tied at 5 runs apiece, the umpires ruled that the ninth inning would be the last to be played.
[src:1938-chicago-cubs-season/1938-chicago-cubs-season] The entire game would have to be replayed the following day if the score remained tied.
[src:1938-chicago-cubs-season/1938-chicago-cubs-season] Hartnett came to bat with two out in the bottom of the ninth inning.
[src:1938-chicago-cubs-season/1938-chicago-cubs-season] With a count of 0 balls and 2 strikes, Hartnett connected on a Mace Brown pitch, launching the ball into the darkness, before it eventually landed in the left-center field bleachers.
[src:1938-chicago-cubs-season/1938-chicago-cubs-season] The stadium erupted into pandemonium as players and fans stormed the field to escort Hartnett around the bases.
[src:1938-chicago-cubs-season/1938-chicago-cubs-season] Hartnett's walk-off home run became immortalized as the *Homer in the Gloamin'*.
[src:1938-chicago-cubs-season/1938-chicago-cubs-season] The Cubs were now in first place, culminating a 19–3–1 record in September, and the pennant would be clinched three days later.
[src:1938-chicago-cubs-season/1938-chicago-cubs-season] It would be 50 years before lights were installed at Wrigley Field.
